n General Manager Andre Shaefer said a one-year agreementhad been reached, but declined to give details.   ``We came to an agreement, and that means no picketing,''Shaefer said. ``It's something we didn't want.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>GOP Consultant: Bush's Gender Gap Problem Could Beat Him InNovember</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Republican political consultant says GeorgeBush will lose in November if he doesn't get the support of morewomen, and that even a woman running mate would not helpsubstantially.   The problem of ``gender gap'' is so serious that overcoming itis probably the most important demographic key to a Bush victory,said Doug Bailey, a respected GOP consultant.   ``If he doesn't bridge the gender gap he will not win ... Thereare not enough white men available for George Bush to win thiselection,'' Bailey said Thursday at a news conference called by theNational Federation of Business and Professional Women's Clubs.   Bailey predicted that Bush, the likely Republican nominee, willwin, however, by making changes in his campaign strategy to makehim more appealing to women voters.   He recommended that the vice president concentrate on making hisown family more visible at campaign appearances, and make a moreforceful commitment to issues like long-term health care, jobsecurity and education.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>South Carolina Senator Favors Texan as Dukakis Running Mate</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., says he isleaning toward Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as a running mate forDemocratic presidential contender Michael Dukakis.   Hollings, who last month said he would support Greenville, S.C.,native Jesse Jackson for president at the Democratic NationalConvention, on Thursday also warned Dukakis against overlyaccommodating the civil rights leader.   ``It was ill-advised under (1984 Democratic nominee Walter)Mondale and now to fall into this same thing of calling him in isnot well-advised,'' Hollings said.   While Hollings reiterated his support for Jackson at thenational convention in Atlanta later this month, he indicated hewould not take a lead role in lobbying for him.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Dukakis Edges Bush in Mock Student Election</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Democrat Michael Dukakis is favored amongstudent voters, if the results of a mock presidential election heldrecently at a meeting of high school student council leaders is anyindication.   The National Association of Secondary School Principals, whichsponsored the event, said Thursday that Dukakis, the probableDemocratic nominee, received 316 votes to 302 for Vice PresidentGeorge Bush, the likely Republican standardbearer.   The ballots were cast last week during the annual conference ofthe National Association of Student Councils in Albuquerque, N.M.   But there was one consolation for the loser: Only 64 of thestudents said they would be old enough to vote in November.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>N.H. Governor Says ``Refugees'' Fleeing Dukakis' Massachusetts</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Republican governor of New Hampshire saystens of thousands of ``refugees'' from Massachusetts are fleeing tohis state each year to escape the policies of Democratic Gov.Michael Dukakis.   ``You ought to stand at the border and talk to them when theycome into New Hampshire,'' said Gov. John Sununu, who is active inRepublican George Bush's presidential campaign, in remarks Thursdayat the National Press Club.   ``The state of Massachusetts in fact has the reality of between50,000 and 100,000 leaving the state in the last five or six years.We in New Hampshire in fact get 10,000 to 20,000 refugees a yearwho escape with their families,'' Sununu said.   ``They have perceived mismanagement, they have perceived apropensity to tax, they're not happy with the quality of servicethey receive,'' said Sununu, who has been speaking around thecountry on Dukakis' record as Massachsuetts governor as part ofBush's surrogate speaker program.</TEXT></DOC>